WEBVTT

00:01.292 --> 00:05.333
How could Ma have had Bunny
and still be so judgmental with me?

00:05.750 --> 00:07.708
BUNNY:
<i>Previously, on</i> Black Cake...

00:07.708 --> 00:09.750
I'm not interested in Jimmy, okay?

00:09.750 --> 00:11.042
He's not my type either.

00:11.042 --> 00:12.042
Then who is?

00:12.042 --> 00:13.458
Come on, tell me!

00:13.458 --> 00:16.125
You! Okay? I like you.

00:16.125 --> 00:17.750
You can't say that.

00:18.458 --> 00:20.375
Bunny, you know rumors
can get people killed.

00:20.833 --> 00:23.625
ELEANOR:
<i>I'm now telling you a secret</i>

00:23.625 --> 00:25.958
<i>I couldn't bring myself
to even share with your father.</i>

00:26.500 --> 00:28.250
<i>You have a sister.</i>

00:28.250 --> 00:29.875
There must be some kind of mistake.
I'm not adopted.

00:29.875 --> 00:32.500
Eleanor was your birth mother.

00:33.250 --> 00:36.208
<i>She wasn't aware that she was adopted.</i>
BENNY: <i>Jesus.</i>

00:36.208 --> 00:38.833
To find out something like that
over the phone.

00:38.833 --> 00:41.000
Let's just finish the last recording.

00:41.000 --> 00:43.583
Your mother was very specific.
She wanted us to wait until

00:43.583 --> 00:46.417
Mabel decided whether or not

00:46.417 --> 00:47.750
she wanted to join us.

00:48.250 --> 00:51.292
MABEL: Did it not occur to you
that I might want to know?

00:51.292 --> 00:53.792
- We were trying to protect you.
- From what?

00:54.125 --> 00:55.792
Calm down, mate, everything's fine.

00:55.792 --> 00:57.750
Was everything fine
when you beat her so bad

00:57.750 --> 00:59.917
she couldn't even show her face
at our dad's funeral?

00:59.917 --> 01:02.208
Oh, you think you can just
swoop in now like a hero?

01:02.500 --> 01:05.458
[Byron grunts]
BENNY: Byron! Byron! Stop!

01:05.458 --> 01:07.583
Stop it, please!

01:07.583 --> 01:08.833
[grunting]

01:08.833 --> 01:10.792
BENNY [echoing]: Stop it, Byron!
POLICE OFFICER [echoing]: Freeze!

01:10.792 --> 01:12.500
Put your hands where we can see them!

01:12.500 --> 01:14.625
Put your hands up, now!

01:24.833 --> 01:27.667
Byron, my sweet boy,

01:29.958 --> 01:31.708
on the day you were born,

01:32.375 --> 01:35.250
your father took
your tiny foot in his hand.

01:36.708 --> 01:40.583
He closed his fingers around it
and just looked at me.

01:41.417 --> 01:43.958
There are no words
for that kind of feeling.

01:46.667 --> 01:48.708
Yes, it was another child
who made me a mother,

01:48.708 --> 01:52.292
but you, Byron... [chuckles]

01:53.250 --> 01:56.333
you were the first time
I got to <i>be</i> a mother.

01:57.708 --> 01:58.875
I had life again.

02:03.458 --> 02:05.750
<i>But even when we bury the truth,</i>

02:07.333 --> 02:08.917
<i>it still eats away at us.</i>
[Benny inaudible]

02:10.792 --> 02:13.917
But I'm grateful now
that I still have time

02:13.917 --> 02:17.042
to right some of the wrongs in my life

02:18.917 --> 02:20.500
before it's too late.

02:21.167 --> 02:25.750
<i>Byron, I'm sorry you felt
so much pressure to be perfect.</i>

02:25.750 --> 02:29.042
I... taught you to bottle things up.

02:30.417 --> 02:32.125
<i>But who can really do that?</i>

02:32.625 --> 02:33.833
<i>And for how long?</i>

02:34.958 --> 02:39.292
<i>And I'm sorry that you felt
that the only way to have our approval</i>

02:39.292 --> 02:41.458
<i>was to do things our way,</i>

02:41.458 --> 02:44.667
<i>even when that meant
leaving your sister out there on her own.</i>

02:47.625 --> 02:50.583
<i>Which brings me to you, Benedetta.</i>

02:53.833 --> 02:55.333
When your father and I

02:57.000 --> 03:01.708
hesitated to embrace you
as you were, you ran.

03:04.917 --> 03:09.792
You were willing to walk away
in order to protect yourself.

03:16.875 --> 03:18.667
You remind me so much of her.

03:22.875 --> 03:24.042
Of Bunny.

03:25.917 --> 03:27.458
And, Benedetta, I--

03:32.875 --> 03:35.875
[Eleanor breathes heavily]

03:42.000 --> 03:43.000
MR. MITCH:
Eleanor?

03:44.000 --> 03:45.000
Are you all right?

03:45.292 --> 03:46.417
[Eleanor sighs]

03:46.875 --> 03:47.708
Tell me.

03:49.167 --> 03:50.167
Please?

03:50.667 --> 03:52.042
I can't get the words out.

03:53.750 --> 03:56.042
Yeah, I've already shared
so many terrible things,

03:56.042 --> 03:57.458
things that happened to me.

03:58.958 --> 04:00.167
[sighs]

04:00.167 --> 04:03.958
I had no idea that this would be
the hardest part to say out loud.

04:04.875 --> 04:05.708
What is?

04:06.208 --> 04:08.292
My choices as a mother.

04:10.667 --> 04:12.792
I've failed them in so many ways.

04:12.792 --> 04:16.083
Eleanor, no,
you are an incredible mother.

04:17.792 --> 04:20.250
Byron thinks the world of you.

04:20.250 --> 04:22.583
[sighs] Because he's his father
through and through.

04:23.583 --> 04:26.083
But even Bert didn't know
everything about my past.

04:27.833 --> 04:30.375
It's a wonder you're still here
after all I've told you.

04:30.375 --> 04:31.417
Oh.

04:34.167 --> 04:36.042
Bert adored you.

04:36.875 --> 04:37.875
Years ago,

04:39.042 --> 04:40.333
before Regina died,

04:41.750 --> 04:45.333
Bert and I used to smoke cigars and <i>boast</i>

04:46.125 --> 04:49.000
[laughing] about our wives

04:49.875 --> 04:51.875
and what great pickers we had.

04:51.875 --> 04:53.875
[both laughing]

04:56.042 --> 04:59.167
Well, we'd seen
so many of our friends' lives

04:59.167 --> 05:01.000
wrecked by divorce.

05:01.958 --> 05:03.000
Hm?

05:03.000 --> 05:04.708
But we hung in there.

05:05.125 --> 05:05.958
Hm.

05:06.125 --> 05:08.792
And we were proud of that.
[slight chuckle]

05:10.000 --> 05:11.083
Two Black men

05:12.708 --> 05:14.083
living the dream,

05:14.875 --> 05:16.000
having it all.

05:18.083 --> 05:20.542
We made it look so easy, didn't we?

05:20.542 --> 05:22.333
Yes.

05:22.333 --> 05:24.708
But you and I both know that it wasn't.

05:25.750 --> 05:26.667
Hm?

05:27.542 --> 05:29.458
Even before we lost them.

05:31.292 --> 05:34.292
[Mr. Mitch sighs]

05:36.625 --> 05:37.625
Maybe

05:39.042 --> 05:41.208
admitting that
you didn't get it all right,

05:42.625 --> 05:45.542
you know, maybe that's one way
of being a better mother.

05:45.542 --> 05:48.583
"I'm sorry" won't rewrite the past.

05:50.000 --> 05:52.125
MR. MITCH: And then tell your children
what you learned from them

05:52.125 --> 05:53.417
by being their mother.

05:54.458 --> 05:56.542
Yeah, maybe
that's what they need to hear most.

06:02.333 --> 06:03.750
[Eleanor breathes deeply]

06:10.208 --> 06:13.167
I'm sorry
things have turned out this way for us.

06:15.083 --> 06:16.125
Sorry for...?

06:16.125 --> 06:17.458
This stupid disease.

06:18.833 --> 06:19.958
MR. MITCH:
Oh.

06:21.208 --> 06:23.208
Oh, no, mm-mm.

06:27.458 --> 06:29.792
[softly]
Well, don't you dare apologize for that.

06:43.042 --> 06:44.125
[Eleanor sighs]

06:49.583 --> 06:50.542
[Mr. Mitch sighs]

06:54.333 --> 06:55.583
Benedetta,

06:57.000 --> 06:58.875
my fearless, bold girl,

06:59.458 --> 07:01.000
you came home to your family,

07:01.000 --> 07:03.750
simply wanting
to be seen for who you were,

07:03.750 --> 07:07.875
and for some reason, I chose to look away.

07:10.333 --> 07:13.750
I was so ashamed
when I realized after you left,

07:14.542 --> 07:17.250
that history was repeating itself.

07:18.833 --> 07:20.833
♪ upbeat calypso rhythm music playing ♪

07:21.583 --> 07:25.500
<i>And that I'd made
the same mistake twice.</i>

07:26.542 --> 07:29.542
[people chattering]
[ocean waves crashing]

07:29.542 --> 07:33.917
♪

07:48.958 --> 07:49.875
ELEANOR: <i>Back then,</i>

07:50.625 --> 07:55.083
<i>I didn't realize
I was telling Bunny to abandon herself,</i>

07:55.833 --> 07:57.292
<i>along with the truth,</i>

07:58.083 --> 08:01.042
<i>when I refused
to acknowledge her feelings for me.</i>

08:01.833 --> 08:02.833
COVEY:
Gibbs!

08:02.833 --> 08:03.833
[Bunny scoffs]

08:05.250 --> 08:06.250
You invited them?

08:07.917 --> 08:09.583
I told you
I didn't want to do a double date.

08:09.583 --> 08:12.167
It's not dating. It's dancing.

08:13.542 --> 08:15.042
I don't wanna lead him on.

08:16.083 --> 08:17.625
Don't look at it that way.

08:17.625 --> 08:19.875
Just... do what I do.

08:20.583 --> 08:23.333
You know, so no one gets the wrong idea.

08:25.375 --> 08:28.375
♪

08:45.583 --> 08:48.583
♪ discordant music playing ♪

09:17.833 --> 09:20.833
♪ discordant music continues playing ♪

09:33.875 --> 09:37.375
ELEANOR:
<i>It was always my intention to protect her.</i>

09:38.208 --> 09:39.583
<i>But I failed her,</i>

09:40.250 --> 09:43.292
<i>just like I failed you, Benedetta.</i>

09:47.333 --> 09:49.000
<i>When I left the island,</i>

09:49.917 --> 09:53.375
<i>Bunny had to fend for herself.</i>

09:55.375 --> 09:59.667
<i>I can't imagine how hard it must've been</i>

10:00.875 --> 10:02.375
<i>to keep hiding,</i>

10:03.833 --> 10:07.583
<i>to feel like there was no other way.</i>

10:11.250 --> 10:12.500
<i>Just like Bunny,</i>

10:13.708 --> 10:16.042
<i>you had to ask yourself,</i>

10:16.042 --> 10:17.458
<i>"What am I willing to do</i>

10:18.417 --> 10:19.792
<i>"to fit in,</i>

10:19.792 --> 10:21.083
<i>"to feel love,</i>

10:22.500 --> 10:23.875
<i>and to survive?"</i>

10:28.583 --> 10:30.083
You sure about this?

10:34.500 --> 10:35.667
[shaky breath]

10:36.292 --> 10:39.292
♪

10:43.458 --> 10:44.792
[Bunny inhales sharply]

10:51.875 --> 10:54.250
ELEANOR:
<i>You did what you had to do.</i>

10:56.500 --> 11:00.833
<i>And I hope you won't be afraid
to make the same kind of choice again.</i>

11:01.583 --> 11:03.000
<i>To walk away.</i>

11:03.542 --> 11:05.167
<i>To refuse to hide.</i>

11:06.583 --> 11:07.583
BENNY:
<i>I felt trapped.</i>

11:09.625 --> 11:11.875
Steve made me feel like if I left,

11:12.750 --> 11:14.167
there was nowhere else I could go.

11:15.708 --> 11:16.708
And I believed him.

11:18.083 --> 11:21.125
Tell me exactly
when the physical violence took place.

11:21.125 --> 11:22.375
Six years ago.

11:23.708 --> 11:24.792
My face was so beaten up,

11:24.792 --> 11:26.750
I couldn't even attend
my father's funeral.

11:27.708 --> 11:29.250
Oh, I'm sorry to hear that.

11:29.250 --> 11:30.083
Yeah.

11:30.917 --> 11:31.917
So was my brother.

11:33.125 --> 11:34.625
I told him yesterday.

11:34.625 --> 11:35.750
That is why we're here.

11:35.750 --> 11:36.958
He's never been in trouble.

11:36.958 --> 11:38.958
He-- He was just trying to protect me.

11:38.958 --> 11:41.750
DETECTIVE: I understand,
but there were eyewitnesses.

11:41.750 --> 11:43.875
He knocked your boyfriend around
pretty good,

11:44.625 --> 11:46.667
and that is aggravated assault.

11:46.667 --> 11:48.917
No, Byron cannot go down for this.

11:50.208 --> 11:51.292
How can I

11:53.500 --> 11:55.208
press charges against Steve?

11:55.208 --> 11:57.750
The statute of limitations
is five years.

11:58.458 --> 11:59.292
[Benny sighs]

11:59.292 --> 12:01.917
Did the abuse continue
after that first incident?

12:04.458 --> 12:05.292
Yes.

12:05.292 --> 12:06.875
Do you have any photographs?

12:08.083 --> 12:09.542
File any reports?

12:09.542 --> 12:11.625
Any documentation of this?

12:11.625 --> 12:13.458
No, I didn't want anybody to know.

12:14.792 --> 12:17.375
DETECTIVE: Ms. Bennett,
you stayed with him for six years.

12:17.375 --> 12:19.083
It'll be difficult to prove.

12:24.083 --> 12:25.833
[detective sighs, clears throat]

12:28.167 --> 12:30.875
If you were to file
an emergency restraining order,

12:31.792 --> 12:34.875
he wouldn't be able
to contact you for 72 hours.

12:34.875 --> 12:37.625
That would buy you time
to seek a court hearing

12:37.625 --> 12:39.583
for a more permanent restraining order.

12:42.750 --> 12:44.458
I'd have to face him in court, right?

12:44.458 --> 12:45.292
DETECTIVE:
Mm-hmm.

12:45.833 --> 12:46.958
Do you wanna proceed?

12:49.042 --> 12:51.042
♪ tense music playing ♪

12:51.375 --> 12:52.792
[police radio chatter]

12:53.833 --> 12:54.833
Right here.

12:56.000 --> 12:57.458
I'm gonna undo your cuffs.

13:00.958 --> 13:02.167
Put your right hand on your head.

13:05.083 --> 13:06.417
Put your left hand on your head.

13:08.292 --> 13:09.125
Turn and face me.

13:10.875 --> 13:13.250
♪

13:14.208 --> 13:16.292
Now, I need you to empty out your pockets.

13:16.292 --> 13:18.542
Place any personal belongings
on the counter.

13:18.542 --> 13:21.542
If you have a belt,
remove that and place it on the counter.

13:21.542 --> 13:23.125
You'll need to remove your watch as well.

13:23.125 --> 13:24.500
Undo your shoelaces.

13:24.500 --> 13:25.333
Place them on the counter.

13:25.333 --> 13:26.708
Hold out your right hand.

13:30.292 --> 13:31.125
Turn around.

13:32.958 --> 13:35.208
[scanner buzzing]

13:38.167 --> 13:40.375
[flashes booming]

13:41.458 --> 13:44.458
♪ tense music continues playing ♪

13:55.000 --> 13:57.750
[indistinct inmate chatter]

14:03.250 --> 14:04.250
OFFICER:
Walk forward.

14:09.958 --> 14:11.125
Put your hand behind your head.

14:11.125 --> 14:13.167
[handcuffs crank]
[Byron winces, exhales sharply]

14:15.208 --> 14:16.042
OFFICER:
Other hand.

14:18.000 --> 14:19.000
Step into the cell.

14:24.500 --> 14:25.708
Turn around.

14:32.375 --> 14:33.375
Sit down.

14:42.083 --> 14:43.208
[cell door clanks shut]

14:49.125 --> 14:51.042
YOUNG BYRON: <i>He called me a little bitch,
so I pushed him.</i>

14:51.042 --> 14:52.083
<i>What was I supposed to do?</i>

14:52.083 --> 14:53.333
BERT:
<i>You walk away.</i>

14:54.125 --> 14:55.208
You tell a teacher.

14:55.208 --> 14:57.167
Why? So she can ask me
what I did to provoke him?

14:57.167 --> 14:58.708
It doesn't matter, Byron.

15:00.792 --> 15:01.625
[Bert sighs]

15:01.625 --> 15:03.250
You can't afford to be angry,

15:04.125 --> 15:05.250
even if it's justified.

15:05.250 --> 15:06.667
That makes no sense.

15:06.667 --> 15:08.208
You're a civil rights attorney.

15:08.208 --> 15:10.833
Your job is to stand up for people,
but I can't stand up for myself?

15:10.833 --> 15:13.500
The rules are different
for you, for me, for all of us.

15:14.667 --> 15:16.208
It's not right, but it's reality.

15:16.208 --> 15:17.042
It's bullshit!

15:17.042 --> 15:18.875
You will watch your mouth in this house!

15:18.875 --> 15:19.792
ELEANOR:
It is.

15:21.125 --> 15:22.958
It <i>is</i> bullshit.

15:23.958 --> 15:24.958
What else?

15:29.042 --> 15:30.167
It's unfair.

15:30.167 --> 15:31.458
What is?

15:31.458 --> 15:32.458
Everything.

15:41.375 --> 15:42.375
Tell us.

15:45.750 --> 15:47.833
My curfew's earlier
than all my friends'.

15:49.958 --> 15:52.750
That I go to a school
where hardly anyone looks like me.

15:54.042 --> 15:56.417
That I can't drive
one mile over the speed limit.

15:56.417 --> 15:58.500
I can't put my hands in my pockets.

15:58.500 --> 16:01.167
That people are surprised
that I'm so articulate.

16:02.250 --> 16:03.875
Everyone else can do
whatever the hell they want

16:03.875 --> 16:04.917
with no consequences,

16:04.917 --> 16:06.917
but I'm expected to be perfect.

16:06.917 --> 16:08.292
ELEANOR:
Oh, my sweet Byron,

16:10.500 --> 16:12.833
that is so much to carry.

16:14.417 --> 16:17.500
I can't pretend that it's not. [sighs]

16:18.500 --> 16:22.750
But the world can be a scary place
for Black boys.

16:27.917 --> 16:28.875
[Byron sniffles]

16:29.792 --> 16:31.375
I know it seems unfair,

16:34.583 --> 16:38.375
but at the end of the day,
we just want you to make it home, son.

16:41.875 --> 16:43.375
You can let it out.

16:44.458 --> 16:46.583
Aw, let it all out...

16:46.583 --> 16:47.708
[Byron sniffling]

16:47.708 --> 16:51.917
...when you are here, at home, with us.

16:56.250 --> 16:57.583
But never out there.

16:59.333 --> 17:00.333
You understand?

17:01.708 --> 17:04.708
♪

17:06.667 --> 17:07.500
[Byron sniffles]

17:18.750 --> 17:21.750
♪ somber music playing ♪

17:25.333 --> 17:27.708
[inmates chattering]

17:34.125 --> 17:35.333
OFFICER:
Bennett!

17:36.250 --> 17:37.542
[cell door alarm buzzes]

17:42.542 --> 17:43.542
OFFICER:
Let's go.

17:48.292 --> 17:49.750
[cell door shuts]
[handcuffs click]

17:57.417 --> 17:59.917
[indistinct chatter]

18:02.958 --> 18:03.792
BENNY:
By!

18:04.958 --> 18:06.667
I'm so sorry. Are you okay?

18:06.667 --> 18:08.458
Thank you, officers. Okay?

18:08.458 --> 18:09.625
Alright.

18:09.625 --> 18:11.292
Everything's been taken care of.

18:11.292 --> 18:12.958
Steve is dropping the charges.

18:13.458 --> 18:14.792
Well, how'd that happen?

18:14.792 --> 18:17.333
OFFICER: Mr. Mitch?
Can I trouble you for a moment please?

18:17.333 --> 18:18.458
You didn't call him, did you?

18:18.458 --> 18:19.708
No!

18:19.708 --> 18:22.208
But I think he's hoping
I'll give him another chance,

18:22.208 --> 18:23.500
which I won't.

18:24.125 --> 18:25.875
I filed a temporary protective order.

18:26.667 --> 18:27.500
So this is done.

18:27.500 --> 18:29.042
It's behind you...
[Byron sighs]

18:29.042 --> 18:30.208
...and that's what matters most.

18:31.792 --> 18:33.167
I'm gonna talk to the prosecutor

18:33.167 --> 18:35.417
and make sure
all the charges are dismissed properly.

18:36.833 --> 18:38.292
You go home, get some rest.

18:38.875 --> 18:42.083
Come on. Let's get you outta here.

18:42.083 --> 18:44.042
[siren wailing]

18:44.792 --> 18:47.292
BENNY: Man, I'm so sorry.
I shouldn't have called you.

18:48.792 --> 18:49.917
BYRON:
Stop.

18:49.917 --> 18:52.167
I'm supposed to be
the person you call, okay?

18:57.250 --> 18:59.500
You know, Ma would've lost her shit
if she saw me in there.

19:00.458 --> 19:01.875
Wait, don't do that to yourself.

19:02.458 --> 19:04.292
Ma kept everything bottled up inside.

19:05.042 --> 19:07.875
Well, she had to record confessions
just so she could die in peace.

19:07.875 --> 19:09.000
Is that what you want?

19:12.292 --> 19:14.417
[distant alarm wails]

19:14.417 --> 19:15.708
I don't know what I want, Ben.

19:19.583 --> 19:22.292
Well, I think Mom would've wanted us
to be able to tell the truth.

19:23.208 --> 19:24.208
And if she were still here,

19:24.208 --> 19:27.167
I think she would've told both of us
that we are allowed to be angry.

19:29.250 --> 19:30.250
Let's go home.

19:33.458 --> 19:34.292
Come on.

19:35.375 --> 19:38.083
I'm supposed to speak
on a diversity panel later on today.

19:39.875 --> 19:40.708
Me,

19:41.458 --> 19:44.750
their prized Black scientist showing up
looking like I just got jumped.

19:44.750 --> 19:45.750
Shit.

19:48.333 --> 19:49.667
That's not a good look.

19:49.667 --> 19:50.625
[Byron scoffs]

19:52.333 --> 19:53.417
[Byron wincing]

19:53.417 --> 19:56.917
BENNY: Uh, at least
the eye gives you some street cred.

19:58.417 --> 19:59.583
Too soon?

19:59.583 --> 20:02.375
You doing my makeup
is your childhood dream come true.

20:02.917 --> 20:07.833
Yeah, well,
it isn't exactly my first rodeo, so...

20:08.417 --> 20:09.333
I'm sorry, Ben.

20:10.000 --> 20:11.167
It's okay.

20:11.167 --> 20:13.083
There's nothing wrong
with a little levity.

20:14.667 --> 20:16.042
[Byron sighs]
- I mean it.

20:16.667 --> 20:19.458
♪ mellow pop music playing on speakers ♪

20:20.583 --> 20:21.417
Take a look.

20:27.250 --> 20:28.083
Yeah.

20:28.958 --> 20:29.958
That should do.

20:33.208 --> 20:35.750
If anyone notices,
I'll just say I have pink eye.

20:35.750 --> 20:36.792
Gross!

20:36.792 --> 20:38.125
Is that the best you can come up with?

20:38.125 --> 20:39.167
Yes.

20:39.167 --> 20:41.417
I'm serious! You are a public figure!

20:41.417 --> 20:42.667
They could cancel you.

20:42.667 --> 20:44.167
[laughs]

20:44.167 --> 20:46.083
Wh-- What could be so funny?

20:46.083 --> 20:48.792
The fact that internet discourse
seems to run in the family.

20:48.792 --> 20:53.042
Turns out Mabel Martin was recently
the subject of some internet controversy.

20:53.833 --> 20:55.792
And you know that how?

20:55.792 --> 20:59.167
I didn't contact her, I just--
I was curious.

21:00.000 --> 21:02.083
You might wanna take a look yourself.

21:02.083 --> 21:04.333
I can't even think about her right now.

21:04.333 --> 21:06.042
I just got you back.

21:06.042 --> 21:10.083
And now Ma wants
to invite this... stranger into our lives.

21:10.083 --> 21:13.042
Yeah, well, you're right, you're right.
We need to focus on each other.

21:16.000 --> 21:16.917
And we will.

21:17.750 --> 21:18.917
Tonight.

21:18.917 --> 21:20.125
I'll cook dinner.

21:20.125 --> 21:21.417
- Yeah?
- Mm-hmm!

21:22.125 --> 21:24.167
Alright.
Alright, look, I gotta go.

21:25.125 --> 21:26.375
Can't wait for dinner.
- Mm-hmm.

21:26.375 --> 21:28.375
- Wish me luck.
- Luck.

21:28.375 --> 21:30.375
BYRON: Eh...
[Benny laughs]

21:32.250 --> 21:33.250
[sighs]

21:33.458 --> 21:35.042
[front door opens, shuts]

21:35.042 --> 21:38.042
♪

21:46.167 --> 21:48.167
[phone chimes]

21:56.708 --> 21:58.083
[sighs]

22:02.083 --> 22:05.083
♪

22:18.583 --> 22:19.417
[phone beeps]

22:23.625 --> 22:25.625
[deep breath]

22:28.542 --> 22:30.542
[indistinct chatter]

22:55.542 --> 22:56.542
[laughs]

23:35.167 --> 23:38.167
♪ somber music playing ♪

23:41.333 --> 23:42.625
[heavy breaths]

23:44.458 --> 23:45.958
[car approaching outside]

23:50.958 --> 23:53.667
[car door opens, closes]

23:54.500 --> 23:55.500
STEVE:
Benny?

23:56.333 --> 23:57.958
[Benny exhales sharply]
[receipts rustling]

24:01.292 --> 24:02.292
STEVE:
Benny!

24:05.125 --> 24:06.125
[Benny sighs]

24:06.125 --> 24:07.542
Benny!

24:10.458 --> 24:11.625
A restraining order?

24:12.750 --> 24:14.458
I mean, what the fuck, Benny?

24:14.458 --> 24:15.458
Please leave.

24:15.458 --> 24:17.292
I dropped the charges
against your brother,

24:17.292 --> 24:18.542
and this is how you pay me back?

24:18.542 --> 24:20.667
I don't wanna call the cops, but I will.

24:21.250 --> 24:23.458
And then you will be arrested,
and your career will be over.

24:23.458 --> 24:24.458
Is that what you want?

24:24.458 --> 24:25.500
I already said I was sorry.

24:25.500 --> 24:27.333
What more do you want from me?
- Nothing!

24:27.333 --> 24:30.208
Steve, that is just it.
I want nothing from you.

24:30.792 --> 24:31.792
It's over!

24:32.708 --> 24:34.500
I'm not gonna ask you again. Leave.

24:34.500 --> 24:35.333
That's it?

24:36.417 --> 24:37.250
That's what you want?

24:37.833 --> 24:39.792
For me to just disappear,

24:39.792 --> 24:42.125
like we didn't spend
six fucking years together!

24:42.125 --> 24:43.500
BENNY:
Just go, please.

24:45.125 --> 24:46.417
I'm not doing this anymore.

24:46.917 --> 24:47.958
You need me, Benny!

24:47.958 --> 24:49.292
That is the thing.

24:49.833 --> 24:51.333
I don't.
- Bullshit!

24:53.500 --> 24:56.208
I mean, what have you created
this past year, huh?

24:57.500 --> 24:58.667
What have you painted,

24:59.583 --> 25:01.542
written, drawn, sculpted even,

25:03.042 --> 25:04.417
that was your own?

25:05.750 --> 25:08.750
♪

25:10.667 --> 25:11.667
And you know what?

25:12.625 --> 25:15.292
The gallery had already sent me
an advance for the piece.

25:15.292 --> 25:16.208
What?

25:16.958 --> 25:18.375
For our sculpture?
STEVE: Yeah.

25:19.667 --> 25:21.417
The one <i>you</i> destroyed.

25:25.083 --> 25:28.000
So how are you gonna come up with $25,000
to pay it back, Benny?

25:29.208 --> 25:32.542
♪

25:36.083 --> 25:37.292
That's not my problem.

25:39.125 --> 25:40.375
You'll figure it out.

25:41.625 --> 25:42.792
You're a parasite.

25:44.708 --> 25:47.167
You had the opportunity
to make something of yourself,

25:47.167 --> 25:48.500
and you blew it.

25:48.500 --> 25:50.042
You don't even know who you are!

25:53.125 --> 25:54.042
[Benny sighs]

25:57.375 --> 25:59.083
At least with me, you were somebody!

26:00.333 --> 26:01.083
Benny!

26:01.750 --> 26:02.583
Benny!

26:02.583 --> 26:04.083
[gasping breaths]

26:06.250 --> 26:07.083
[applause]

26:07.083 --> 26:10.125
Your organization has been
at the forefront of these initiatives

26:10.125 --> 26:12.750
to increase equity in oceanic study.

26:12.750 --> 26:14.125
So my question is,

26:14.125 --> 26:17.833
what do you believe other organizations
who are lagging in this area

26:17.833 --> 26:19.292
need to hear right now?

26:20.125 --> 26:20.958
[Marc clears throat]

26:21.542 --> 26:24.792
Well, for one, they need to hear

26:24.792 --> 26:27.875
that the ocean doesn't belong
to any one group of people.

26:28.708 --> 26:31.958
And protecting it and exploring it

26:31.958 --> 26:34.000
isn't the duty
of just one group of people,

26:34.000 --> 26:35.833
it's a job for all of us.

26:35.833 --> 26:40.083
Scientists from underrepresented groups
deserve to be a part of that,

26:40.750 --> 26:41.917
deserve to get funding,

26:42.500 --> 26:46.167
deserve to be represented in this field.

26:47.500 --> 26:49.500
[audience applauding]

26:53.667 --> 26:55.875
MARC:
Take sea floor mapping, for example,

26:55.875 --> 26:57.792
led by Byron Bennett here.

26:57.792 --> 27:02.167
His team's research allows us to monitor
and protect our underwater resources.

27:02.167 --> 27:04.333
And we're just so proud

27:04.333 --> 27:10.208
to have fostered the career
of such a dynamic, passionate scientist.

27:11.042 --> 27:13.250
[chuckles] My God, look at that smile.

27:13.250 --> 27:15.792
[audience laughing, applauding]
[camera shutter snapping]

27:19.542 --> 27:21.250
At this time,
we'd love to invite the audience

27:21.250 --> 27:22.500
to ask any questions.

27:23.250 --> 27:24.250
Yes, go ahead.

27:24.958 --> 27:27.500
Byron, what example do you hope to be

27:27.500 --> 27:30.250
for the next generation
of scientists in your field?

27:33.458 --> 27:38.250
Well, I hope young people
from marginalized communities

27:38.250 --> 27:39.750
see themselves in me,

27:39.750 --> 27:43.083
and realize that
if it was possible for me,

27:43.083 --> 27:46.208
then it's possible for them.
[camera shutter snapping]

27:46.792 --> 27:48.375
[audience applauding]

27:52.042 --> 27:54.208
Yes, you at the back there.
Yes, what's your question?

27:54.208 --> 27:56.125
It's for Dr. Bennett, as well.

27:57.083 --> 27:59.125
What's it like being a trailblazer,

27:59.792 --> 28:02.208
to be the first Black man in your position

28:02.208 --> 28:05.000
at a big, prestigious institution
such as yours?

28:08.667 --> 28:09.667
Good question.

28:12.542 --> 28:15.792
Uh, I've been
thinking a lot about that lately.

28:16.417 --> 28:18.208
I have an incredible life.

28:19.042 --> 28:23.167
I get to travel the world
doing something that I love.

28:23.167 --> 28:27.042
And for that... I'm grateful.

28:28.542 --> 28:32.167
But there's more
to this work than traveling and

28:33.750 --> 28:35.458
making appearances.

28:39.208 --> 28:40.667
The day-to-day can be

28:44.625 --> 28:46.125
traumatizing.

28:46.125 --> 28:48.125
[audience murmuring]

28:50.708 --> 28:51.708
That's the truth.

28:53.000 --> 28:55.833
To be the only person in the room
who looks like you,

28:56.667 --> 29:00.875
the only person forced
to deal with the daily microaggressions

29:00.875 --> 29:02.292
that wear away at you.

29:02.292 --> 29:05.208
I mean, it's stressful, man,

29:06.792 --> 29:08.125
and lonely,

29:09.208 --> 29:11.375
and exhausting.

29:12.500 --> 29:14.167
[camera shutter snapping]

29:14.167 --> 29:16.500
I'm tired of doing these panels,

29:17.000 --> 29:18.625
but I'm obligated to do them,

29:19.125 --> 29:20.708
'cause I'm the only one who can.

29:20.708 --> 29:22.500
Now for a long time,

29:22.500 --> 29:24.292
I pretended to be fine with it.

29:25.833 --> 29:26.833
Honestly,

29:28.458 --> 29:30.083
it makes me angry,

29:30.083 --> 29:32.750
and I'm <i>learning</i> to <i>listen</i> to that anger,

29:32.750 --> 29:34.292
because it tells you that

29:35.000 --> 29:40.750
even though all of these people
are smiling in your face,

29:41.500 --> 29:43.750
something is very wrong here.

29:45.250 --> 29:47.750
Well, those were
some very powerful sentiments--

29:47.750 --> 29:49.292
I'm not finished.

29:49.292 --> 29:51.500
[audience murmuring]

29:53.542 --> 29:57.125
BYRON:
That anger, you have to use it, right?

29:58.417 --> 30:01.917
But use it for good.

30:01.917 --> 30:05.542
Now, we have to create a space
for this important, planet-saving work.

30:05.542 --> 30:07.750
A space where
I don't have to be the only one.

30:08.250 --> 30:12.333
And that is gonna be a long, hard battle,

30:12.333 --> 30:17.000
because these institutions,
they don't <i>want</i> to share power with you.

30:17.000 --> 30:17.833
No.

30:19.042 --> 30:20.542
You'll have to fight for that.

30:20.542 --> 30:22.500
[softly] Byron, why don't we
open up the discussion?

30:23.833 --> 30:25.667
When the people
running these institutions

30:25.667 --> 30:28.708
picture their next CEO,
chairman, director,

30:29.375 --> 30:31.917
they are <i>not</i> imagining my face.

30:33.042 --> 30:36.458
They imagine someone
who looks like my colleague here, right?

30:38.583 --> 30:43.667
Now we, as people of color,
don't occupy their imagination

30:43.667 --> 30:45.500
the way they occupy ours.

30:47.125 --> 30:48.458
So we have to fight

30:49.458 --> 30:51.250
to fix broken systems.

30:52.792 --> 30:54.500
And this is certainly one of them.

30:59.625 --> 31:02.625
[audience applauding]

31:32.625 --> 31:35.125
[phone vibrating]

31:48.542 --> 31:50.500
BYRON [on video]:
<i>When the people running these institutions</i>

31:50.500 --> 31:53.875
<i>picture their next CEO,
chairman, director,</i>

31:54.292 --> 31:57.042
<i>they are</i> not <i>imagining
someone with my face.</i>

32:07.208 --> 32:08.083
[Byron sighs]

32:11.458 --> 32:14.458
[car engine rumbling]

32:14.458 --> 32:16.750
♪ tense music playing ♪

32:27.500 --> 32:29.583
[tapping on phone]

32:30.250 --> 32:32.208
[line ringing]

32:32.208 --> 32:35.083
BENNY [over voice mail]: <i>This is Benny.
Don't leave a message, just text.</i>

32:49.625 --> 32:52.625
♪ tense music continues ♪

33:03.792 --> 33:06.417
<i>♪ Way Over My Head</i> by Chi Duly
and Love Taps plays loudly over speakers ♪

33:06.417 --> 33:08.792
[food sizzling]

33:10.125 --> 33:14.375
<i>♪ I wanna, I wanna,
I want no space between us ♪</i>

33:14.375 --> 33:16.000
<i>♪ I know that, I know that... ♪</i>
[front door opens]

33:16.000 --> 33:17.583
Dinner in five, By!

33:18.250 --> 33:19.833
By, you want me to make you a drink?

33:20.500 --> 33:22.458
You're gonna need one
when I show you what I found.

33:24.250 --> 33:25.542
<i>♪ I wanna, I wanna... ♪</i>

33:25.542 --> 33:26.958
BENNY:
How was your panel?

33:26.958 --> 33:28.458
Did you solve racism?

33:29.167 --> 33:33.333
<i>♪ I wanna, I wanna,
I want no space between us ♪</i>

33:33.750 --> 33:35.542
<i>♪ I know that, I know that,
I know that they-- ♪</i>

33:35.542 --> 33:36.542
♪ music stops ♪

33:37.000 --> 33:38.000
[Byron clears throat]

33:38.542 --> 33:41.000
Benny, this is Mabel Martin.

33:43.667 --> 33:44.667
Hello.

33:48.750 --> 33:50.583
Mabel, this is my sister, Benny.

33:52.458 --> 33:53.292
Hi.

33:55.000 --> 33:55.833
Hello.

33:56.875 --> 33:59.792
I'm sorry,
it, uh, wasn't my intention to intrude.

33:59.792 --> 34:03.250
Your lawyer, Mr. Charles Mitch,
he invited me to come out.

34:04.000 --> 34:05.833
He provided your mother's address.

34:05.833 --> 34:08.417
Hey, yeah, I mean, it's okay.

34:08.417 --> 34:09.833
We're glad you're here.

34:10.250 --> 34:11.250
Right, Benny?

34:14.458 --> 34:17.083
Admittedly, I wasn't sure
I was ready to meet you both.

34:19.667 --> 34:22.500
I hoped once I arrived here,
it'd become clearer to me.

34:23.417 --> 34:26.208
I jumped on a plane
without thinking about it.

34:26.208 --> 34:28.208
Oh, well. Um, are you hungry?

34:29.333 --> 34:31.375
I should be, I haven't eaten in a day.

34:31.375 --> 34:32.458
Alright, okay.

34:32.458 --> 34:36.125
Um, Ben, could you, uh,
set the table for one more, please?

34:36.125 --> 34:37.667
Or two, actually.

34:37.667 --> 34:40.333
I guess we need to call Mr. Mitch
so we could proceed.

34:43.958 --> 34:44.958
Ben?
[Benny gasps]

34:45.917 --> 34:47.458
Y-Yeah, gimme a sec.
[slight chuckle]

34:50.208 --> 34:52.208
[dishes clattering]

34:54.417 --> 34:56.000
I'm sorry, could I use your loo?

34:56.000 --> 34:57.250
Yeah, of course.

34:57.250 --> 34:59.792
Just through here,
second door on the left.

35:06.708 --> 35:08.250
[cutlery clattering]

35:08.250 --> 35:09.250
[Byron exhales sharply]

35:09.750 --> 35:10.792
BYRON: Yo.

35:33.958 --> 35:36.667
Hey, sooner or later,
you're gonna have to talk to her.

35:38.250 --> 35:41.125
♪ soft folk-pop music playing ♪

35:45.417 --> 35:48.625
Your lawyer, Mr. Mitch,
does he live far or...?

35:48.625 --> 35:50.875
Oh, no. He should be here soon.

35:51.792 --> 35:52.792
Oh, okay.

35:53.417 --> 35:54.250
Good.

35:59.417 --> 36:00.833
You are quite the cook.

36:03.292 --> 36:04.125
I try.

36:05.042 --> 36:06.583
It's not like you, though.

36:06.583 --> 36:09.167
MABEL: Oh, no.
No, the food is divine, really.

36:09.167 --> 36:12.208
I love za’atar on eggplant.
It's a great combination.

36:14.625 --> 36:18.625
I use a Syrian blend.
It's a little heavier on the sumac.

36:18.625 --> 36:20.625
Makes it red instead of green.

36:21.292 --> 36:22.458
Adds a bit of flair.

36:22.458 --> 36:23.292
[chuckles]

36:23.292 --> 36:24.917
No, it's gorgeous.

36:24.917 --> 36:27.583
It's always worth it
to source the imported stuff.

36:27.583 --> 36:31.250
Experimenting with the same ingredient
from different regions, it's <i>very</i> smart.

36:32.042 --> 36:33.583
Not everyone has that instinct.

36:34.417 --> 36:36.583
Yeah, Byron can't tell the difference.

36:36.583 --> 36:38.500
[both women laughing]

36:38.500 --> 36:42.708
MABEL: Your style reminds me
of a brilliant chef named Habiba Davis.
[phone vibrating]

36:42.708 --> 36:45.292
MABEL: Do you know her?
BENNY: Know her? [laughs]

36:45.292 --> 36:48.625
No. I do own a few of her books.

36:49.708 --> 36:51.583
I really admire her, actually.

36:53.250 --> 36:56.083
Wait, you don't <i>know her</i> know her, do you?

36:57.667 --> 37:00.750
Well, our paths have crossed
at a few events,

37:01.250 --> 37:03.083
but it's mostly been
me embarrassing myself

37:03.083 --> 37:04.375
by fawning all over her.

37:04.375 --> 37:06.500
[both laughing]

37:10.958 --> 37:12.667
Do you have a favorite cuisine?

37:12.667 --> 37:14.625
Or something
that you like to cook for dinner?

37:16.042 --> 37:18.208
MABEL:
Oh, goodness, um,

37:19.958 --> 37:22.125
I actually like breakfast for dinner.

37:22.792 --> 37:25.792
[laughs] That's a--
My dirty secret, I guess.

37:25.792 --> 37:28.250
[all politely chuckling]

37:36.042 --> 37:37.167
Is something wrong?

37:37.167 --> 37:39.000
No, no.

37:39.000 --> 37:43.792
It's just... the way you tuck your hair
behind your ear,

37:43.792 --> 37:46.833
just, um... reminds me of our mother.

37:46.833 --> 37:47.833
It's totally Ma.

37:48.500 --> 37:49.500
BYRON:
<i>Your</i> mother.

37:49.500 --> 37:50.750
Uh-- [sharp exhale]

37:50.750 --> 37:52.833
<i>Our</i> mother. Sorry.
BENNY: Mm-hmm.

37:54.625 --> 37:55.625
Your mum.

37:59.375 --> 38:01.250
[doorbell rings]
- [clears throat] Oh.

38:02.708 --> 38:04.375
That should be Mr. Mitch.

38:11.167 --> 38:13.167
[keyboard clacking]

38:18.458 --> 38:21.292
Um, may I ask,
what happened to your eye?

38:24.042 --> 38:28.125
Oh, Byron and my ex, they got into it.

38:28.875 --> 38:30.708
It wasn't pretty, obviously. [chuckles]

38:31.208 --> 38:36.375
But he was being an amazing brother,
and he was looking out for me.

38:38.792 --> 38:39.792
You know,

38:41.125 --> 38:44.292
Byron is actually
sort of internet famous, too.

38:44.292 --> 38:46.000
I mean, in the science world.

38:46.750 --> 38:47.958
Oh, is that so?

38:47.958 --> 38:50.708
Yeah, so he is under a lot of pressure.

38:50.708 --> 38:55.125
I mean, you get it, going through
this whole Culinary Karen thing.

38:56.208 --> 38:58.125
Oh, that, yeah.

38:59.917 --> 39:01.375
But the funny thing is,

39:01.917 --> 39:05.583
you are actually Black <i>and</i> Chinese,

39:05.583 --> 39:10.000
so you can tell them all
to fuck off now. [laughs]

39:12.167 --> 39:13.875
Yeah. I suppose I am.

39:14.667 --> 39:16.000
Hasn't really sunk in yet.

39:16.000 --> 39:17.958
Of course, it hasn't.
[slight chuckle]

39:17.958 --> 39:20.500
I mean, it's been like, what, 24 hours?

39:22.750 --> 39:23.750
Yeah.

39:26.792 --> 39:28.125
But what else am I?

39:28.750 --> 39:31.917
I mean, clearly,
we don't have the same father.

39:31.917 --> 39:35.542
Your mum, did she mention
my birth father in the recordings?

39:38.375 --> 39:44.125
Eleanor, actually,
left you a separate recording, Mabel.

39:44.708 --> 39:46.958
One just for you
that, hopefully, will answer

39:48.458 --> 39:50.125
most of your questions.

39:50.708 --> 39:53.250
But, uh, tonight,

39:53.875 --> 39:58.792
she wanted the three of you
to listen to this last recording together.

39:59.875 --> 40:02.792
Right. Well, respectfully,
I'd appreciate if you tell me now,

40:02.792 --> 40:05.708
seeing as you...
clearly, all know something.

40:07.250 --> 40:08.250
[Mr. Mitch clears throat]

40:13.583 --> 40:17.875
Our mom lived in Scotland
for a brief time many years ago.

40:18.708 --> 40:19.833
During her time there,

40:19.833 --> 40:23.000
she found work
at a textile trading company.

40:23.625 --> 40:25.750
Oh. So she met someone there?

40:27.167 --> 40:30.167
♪ solemn music playing ♪

40:32.542 --> 40:33.875
She was assaulted

40:34.875 --> 40:37.875
by her employer
around the time you were born.

40:41.375 --> 40:42.375
Assaulted?

40:44.500 --> 40:45.375
That she was--

40:50.958 --> 40:51.792
Right.

40:55.375 --> 40:56.208
[scoffs]

40:58.042 --> 40:59.750
Coming here was a mistake.

40:59.750 --> 41:01.375
I, I wasn't thinking clearly.

41:01.375 --> 41:03.083
Um, I don't-- I--
I don't wanna hear anything more.

41:03.083 --> 41:05.167
BYRON:
We are not trying to be cruel.

41:05.167 --> 41:08.792
But <i>our</i> mother,
she wanted us to listen to this together.

41:08.792 --> 41:11.583
No, <i>your</i> mum
wanted <i>you</i> to listen to this.

41:12.792 --> 41:15.125
I have no obligation
to this person who raised you.

41:15.625 --> 41:16.750
I didn't know her.

41:16.750 --> 41:18.625
She was a stranger, as are you.

41:19.250 --> 41:21.500
Whatever's in the estate,
I don't want anything.

41:21.500 --> 41:23.292
I'll forfeit whatever
was designated to me.

41:26.375 --> 41:28.208
I am very sorry for your loss.

41:29.417 --> 41:31.333
You can listen
to the rest of the recordings without me.

41:31.333 --> 41:33.042
I'm not coming back here.
- Wait, Mabel, wait.

41:33.042 --> 41:34.042
Look,

41:35.958 --> 41:37.917
I hope you find
the answers you're looking for.

41:41.333 --> 41:42.333
[scoffs]

41:48.125 --> 41:49.125
[door slams shut]

41:51.958 --> 41:54.542
Well, your mother hoped
that things would go differently,

41:54.542 --> 41:56.167
but she knew, in all likelihood,

41:56.167 --> 41:58.292
it wouldn't go
exactly according to her plan.

41:58.292 --> 42:02.792
So... if you both agree,
we can move on without Mabel.

42:02.792 --> 42:06.000
And I can play the final recording
if that's what you want.

42:06.000 --> 42:07.125
Yes.
BENNY: No.

42:08.500 --> 42:09.750
What do you want us to do?

42:10.375 --> 42:11.708
Wait for her to come around?

42:11.708 --> 42:13.542
That could take days or years, Ben.

42:13.542 --> 42:17.667
Wha-- Ma was <i>dying</i> and all she wanted
was for us to know Mabel.

42:17.667 --> 42:19.750
But Mabel doesn't want to know <i>us.</i>

42:19.750 --> 42:22.500
Can't you see that she reacted that way
because she's in pain?

42:23.417 --> 42:25.500
She didn't even know she was adopted,

42:25.500 --> 42:28.208
that her parents... weren't her parents.

42:28.208 --> 42:30.042
When I walked outta here on Thanksgiving,

42:30.042 --> 42:33.208
all I wanted was
for somebody to come to me

42:33.208 --> 42:35.375
and <i>dare</i> me to stick around,

42:36.417 --> 42:37.833
and nobody did.

42:37.833 --> 42:40.208
I am not about to let
the same thing happen to Mabel.

42:41.542 --> 42:42.958
We tried, Ben.

42:44.375 --> 42:46.208
We did not try hard enough.

42:47.042 --> 42:48.333
Ma didn't, either.

42:49.000 --> 42:51.583
I mean, she called and she wrote,
but that wasn't enough.

42:52.208 --> 42:55.167
And Dad, he probably thought he had
all the time in the world to fix things,

42:55.167 --> 42:57.750
but... he didn't do enough either.

43:07.417 --> 43:08.500
What's that?

43:08.500 --> 43:12.542
Receipts from cafes and shops
<i>across</i> the street from my apartment.

43:14.167 --> 43:17.417
Did you know that he was driving up
to Highland Park every month?

43:17.917 --> 43:19.000
What-- Of course not.

43:19.958 --> 43:22.500
Yeah, I guess Ma didn't either.

43:22.500 --> 43:24.583
I don't know
when she found all this, but

43:26.292 --> 43:27.458
he was right there, By.

43:28.542 --> 43:31.000
He was <i>across</i> the street from me,

43:32.250 --> 43:34.250
[voice breaking] and he couldn't even
knock on my door.

43:36.625 --> 43:38.292
I need to do this.

43:39.000 --> 43:42.417
And I need you to believe for a moment

43:42.417 --> 43:44.333
that maybe, just maybe,

43:45.875 --> 43:47.750
I can do one thing right on my own.

43:53.333 --> 43:54.333
Fine.

43:55.250 --> 43:56.833
If you want to go after her

43:57.417 --> 43:58.875
and get your heart broken,

44:01.292 --> 44:02.125
go.

44:04.833 --> 44:05.833
I'll be back.

44:14.833 --> 44:17.833
♪

44:27.708 --> 44:30.708
[waves crashing]

44:52.583 --> 44:53.583
[exhales]

45:00.333 --> 45:01.167
[slight wince]

45:08.542 --> 45:10.542
[shower running]

45:33.417 --> 45:36.167
♪

45:58.958 --> 46:00.750
[grunts] Fuck!

46:00.750 --> 46:02.042
[knocking on door]

46:02.042 --> 46:03.042
Um...

46:03.833 --> 46:05.542
All right, I'm coming.

46:27.917 --> 46:30.667
- Hi.
- I'm sorry, you're wasting your time.

46:30.667 --> 46:32.583
I've already rescheduled my flight.
BENNY: I understand.

46:32.583 --> 46:34.917
I just wanna have a conversation with you
before you leave.

46:36.917 --> 46:39.958
I brought some food from
a little hole-in-the-wall Jamaican joint.

46:39.958 --> 46:42.417
They got a B health inspection rating
on the window.

46:43.375 --> 46:44.542
With the folding tables

46:44.542 --> 46:46.125
and the plastic chairs
that stick to your legs?

46:46.125 --> 46:48.500
Yep. Kitchen run by a granny.

46:48.500 --> 46:49.625
I watched her make this.

46:49.625 --> 46:50.833
Doesn't get more authentic.

46:51.417 --> 46:53.417
Ackee and saltfish.

46:53.417 --> 46:56.083
- Breakfast for dinner.
- Your favorite!

46:56.083 --> 46:57.792
You know,
it's really rather manipulative

46:57.792 --> 46:58.750
that you remembered that.

46:59.833 --> 47:00.833
Shall we?

47:12.333 --> 47:13.167
Whoa.

47:15.750 --> 47:17.292
Sorry, I came on so strong.

47:18.375 --> 47:20.875
I can be... intense.

47:20.875 --> 47:22.000
[both chuckle]

47:23.750 --> 47:26.500
But... I do have something
I wanna say to you.

47:29.708 --> 47:32.792
I always thought there was something wrong
or off with my ma.

47:34.250 --> 47:36.208
I always thought
that she was comparing me to Byron,

47:36.208 --> 47:37.833
but now it all makes sense,

47:38.375 --> 47:40.708
that <i>you</i> were the missing piece.

47:42.125 --> 47:43.208
She was grieving you.

47:48.458 --> 47:50.708
I wish I knew
what to do with that, Benny.

47:51.875 --> 47:53.042
Or how to feel.

47:54.333 --> 47:55.458
But I didn't know her.

47:56.542 --> 47:58.708
It doesn't mean to me
what it means to you.

47:59.208 --> 48:03.167
It sounds like your mum's recordings
are answering questions for you,

48:03.750 --> 48:05.542
but they're raising questions for me.

48:07.375 --> 48:09.125
My whole world has shifted.

48:09.750 --> 48:10.750
My identity.

48:12.000 --> 48:15.542
I haven't even begun to look back
and ask myself how didn't I know?

48:15.542 --> 48:17.083
What did I miss?

48:17.083 --> 48:18.708
And I'm not ready to do that right now.

48:20.375 --> 48:22.750
And I'm afraid
of what learning about my birth father

48:23.667 --> 48:24.667
will mean.

48:25.417 --> 48:26.417
Not just to me,

48:28.083 --> 48:29.167
but to my parents,

48:30.292 --> 48:31.458
and to my son.

48:32.125 --> 48:33.125
Your son?

48:34.667 --> 48:35.500
Gio.

48:36.000 --> 48:37.000
He's 16.

48:38.625 --> 48:39.625
He is

48:41.000 --> 48:42.792
beautiful,

48:42.792 --> 48:43.792
brazen,

48:45.000 --> 48:46.125
infuriating.

48:46.125 --> 48:48.625
[both chuckling]

48:48.625 --> 48:49.625
He's my world.

48:52.542 --> 48:55.125
And there's things that
he doesn't know about his own father.

48:56.917 --> 48:58.333
Things I don't want him to learn.

48:59.542 --> 49:00.542
Well, where is he?

49:01.458 --> 49:02.458
Your son's dad?

49:02.458 --> 49:04.042
[clears throat] It-- It doesn't matter.

49:04.042 --> 49:05.625
I don't know why I'm dwelling on the past.

49:05.625 --> 49:06.792
Must be the gin talking.

49:07.708 --> 49:08.542
BENNY:
Uh--

49:08.875 --> 49:10.625
I don't wanna speak outta turn, Mabel,

49:10.625 --> 49:13.375
'cause this is absolutely
none of my business, but

49:14.333 --> 49:15.708
I think you have to ask yourself,

49:15.708 --> 49:17.833
are you keeping things from Gio
to protect him

49:18.750 --> 49:21.125
or because you're afraid
of how he'll see you?

49:21.708 --> 49:22.542
Both.

49:24.917 --> 49:28.333
And I am of the belief
that some secrets are best left buried.

49:33.667 --> 49:34.958
Can I ask you something?

49:36.208 --> 49:37.208
Of course.

49:38.833 --> 49:41.917
Do you remember speaking
to an elderly woman with an island accent

49:41.917 --> 49:43.083
on the phone, ever?

49:45.000 --> 49:45.833
No.

49:46.333 --> 49:47.333
I'm sorry, why?

49:48.042 --> 49:51.292
[sighs] 'Cause Byron told me
about these outgoing calls

49:51.292 --> 49:52.875
he found on Ma's cell.

49:54.208 --> 49:55.375
Calls she made to you.

49:56.000 --> 49:59.625
Maybe she called you under false pretenses
or under a fake name,

49:59.625 --> 50:02.500
'cause... that was kind of her thing.

50:04.917 --> 50:05.750
Actually,

50:06.542 --> 50:10.000
I have been getting some odd phone calls
over the past year or so.

50:10.000 --> 50:11.417
The person would call,

50:11.917 --> 50:14.125
sit quietly for a while
after I've answered,

50:14.125 --> 50:16.542
and then... just hang up.

50:18.125 --> 50:20.167
I've never thought anything of it,

50:21.333 --> 50:22.333
but it may have been her.

50:23.250 --> 50:25.750
She must have started doing that
after her diagnosis.

50:27.417 --> 50:28.417
[sighs]

50:30.292 --> 50:31.958
It's all so ironic.

50:33.000 --> 50:33.833
MABEL:
What is?

50:35.292 --> 50:36.292
[Benny sighs]

50:37.208 --> 50:39.625
BENNY: I had a falling out with my dad
before he died.

50:41.250 --> 50:43.792
And he never picked up the phone
in two years.

50:43.792 --> 50:46.167
I mean, he wanted to,
but he ran out of time.

50:47.458 --> 50:50.125
And I'll never know
what he was so afraid to say.

50:53.375 --> 50:57.000
Aren't you curious
what my mom wanted to tell you?

50:59.125 --> 51:01.292
Of course, I'm curious.

51:01.292 --> 51:05.167
Isn't it better to <i>know</i>
what she wanted to say than wonder?

51:06.458 --> 51:08.083
I mean, maybe she could tell you something

51:08.083 --> 51:10.250
that you didn't even know
you needed to hear.

51:10.833 --> 51:13.833
♪ pensive music playing ♪

51:22.333 --> 51:23.750
BYRON:
Thank you for staying.

51:23.750 --> 51:24.750
MR. MITCH:
Of course.

51:26.292 --> 51:27.292
You ready?

51:27.292 --> 51:28.292
BYRON:
Yeah.

51:33.000 --> 51:34.000
Sweet enough?

51:35.708 --> 51:36.708
It's delicious.

51:38.875 --> 51:40.875
♪

51:52.417 --> 51:53.625
[sighs] This is it.

51:54.917 --> 51:55.917
The last recording.

51:58.750 --> 51:59.750
You ready, brother?

52:02.625 --> 52:03.458
Mabel?

52:10.917 --> 52:12.250
Alrighty then.

52:13.708 --> 52:14.625
Here we go.

52:15.958 --> 52:16.792
[clicks touchpad]

52:17.917 --> 52:19.083
ELEANOR [on recording]:
<i>B and B,</i>

52:19.875 --> 52:22.375
<i>I'm about to share
something else with you,</i>

52:23.333 --> 52:25.625
<i>something I haven't before.</i>

52:27.125 --> 52:28.208
<i>But first,</i>

52:28.958 --> 52:31.500
<i>I want to say something to your sister,</i>

52:33.083 --> 52:35.583
<i>to Mabel Mathilda.</i>

52:37.708 --> 52:38.708
<i>Mabel,</i>

52:40.083 --> 52:42.417
<i>my firstborn,</i>

52:44.125 --> 52:46.750
<i>there is so much I want to tell you.</i>

52:48.000 --> 52:49.000
<i>But first,</i>

52:50.708 --> 52:52.542
<i>you were loved.</i>

52:53.917 --> 52:55.542
<i>The moment I held you,</i>

52:55.542 --> 52:59.708
<i>I knew I wanted to be your mother.</i>

53:01.250 --> 53:02.583
<i>But by that point,</i>

53:03.583 --> 53:05.292
<i>it was out of my control.</i>

53:06.708 --> 53:10.083
<i>By that point, it was too late.</i>

53:11.667 --> 53:13.167
<i>Because the truth is,</i>

53:13.833 --> 53:16.833
<i>I didn't choose to let you go.</i>

53:19.792 --> 53:21.333
<i>You were taken from me.</i>

53:23.125 --> 53:26.125
♪ somber music playing ♪

53:38.208 --> 53:41.708
♪

54:24.625 --> 54:26.625
♪

54:47.125 --> 54:48.583
♪

55:21.292 --> 55:24.125
♪

55:24.125 --> 55:26.292
♪ music fades out ♪
